A descriptive, multicenter, international, longitudinal, retrospective, chart review study
In May 2023, regulatory submission for the SERVIER NALLONG study was initiated and the
first Study Initiation Visit occurred in August in Japan. This real-world study seeks to evaluate
long-term survival metastatic pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (mPDAC) patients after
treatment with liposomal irinotecan.
Background PDAC
Pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) is the most common type of pancreatic
malignancy and accounts for >90% of all pancreatic cancer cases.1Patients with PDAC
show no early symptoms and are mostly diagnosed at a locally advanced (20-30%) or
metastatic (50-55%) stage, often precluding potentially curative resection.2,3

Real-world evidence on patients with metastatic pancreatic ductal
adenocarcinoma long-term survival after treatment with liposomal irinotecan
Study objectives
NALLONG will be a descriptive, multicentre, international, longitudinal, retrospective chart
review study of mPDAC patients who survived 1 year after initiating a treatment with nal-IRI
following a gemcitabine-based regimen.
Objectives
Characterize the mPDAC patient population according to their demographics
1
Identify PDAC treatment by line of treatment from diagnosis to last treatment
2
Explore prognostic factors of longer OS and PFS among mPDAC patients showing
long-term survival
3
Japan South KoreaBelgium GermanyAustria
Study countries
=150 patients =20 sites
Study rationale
Compared to the NAPOLI-1 trial, in clinical routine mPDAC patients tend to be9,10:
have poorer ECOG performance status
older
have experienced more lines of therapy
The NAPOLI-1 trial (nal-IRI+5-FU/LV vs 5-FU/LV: median overall survival 6.2 months vs 4.2
months, 12 month overall rate 26% vs 16% respectively) identified characteristics of long-term
survival mPDAC patients but was restricted by the small sample size of this subgroup
analysis.8Further, given the differences in characteristics of patients in clinical routine, it is
imperative to collect additional clinical outcomes in the real-world setting, to support
regulatory decision-making and to guide clinical practice.
mPDAC patients in clinical routine
